The paper deals with coordination mechanisms and equilibrium inefficiency in scheduling games, which are topics that fall under game theory (cs.GT) and algorithms (cs.DS). The use of smooth arguments and inequalities suggests a focus on optimization and analysis, which are also relevant to machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the consideration of different levels of knowledge about jobs implies a potential connection to information theory (cs.IT).
